Protests.FactsFound: GBR9177 and DEN9055 on the second beat to windward with GBR on STB and DEN on port tack on a converging courses pointing bow to bow. Weather condition 18kn Wind, wave about 1m. At a distance of 2 boat length DEN luffed and stopped head to wind. GBR bore away hard, passing astern of DEN. Contact occurred between boom of DEN and Crew's back of GBR resulting in a bruce. GBR capsized within a minute after incident. DEN took a penalty turn. Both boats finished the race without a less functional crew.
Protests.Conclusion:
By not keeping clear of GBR on STB tack DEN on port broke RRS 10.
As the contact did not made the crew of GBR9177 less functional during the remaining part of race nr. 5 the requirement of injury as of RRS62.1(b) is not met.
Protests.Decision: Requirement of RRS 62.1(b) is not fully met as even a bruce occurred the crew was not made less functional during the remaining part of race nr. 5, and is therefore not considered as injury.
Protests.ProceduralMatters:
Incident occured 13:45
Boat went home to pick up medication

Protests.FactsFound:
On the first run Crew of GER9130 fell into the water. Crew got seperated by several hundred of meters to the boat.
GER9135 observed the incident, tacked and returned to the person in the water. 9135 picked the crew of 9130 up and returned him to the boat.
Protests.Conclusion: GER9135 gave help to a person in danger and made her own position worse.
Protests.Decision:
By giving help to a person in danger GER9135 position was made worse by no fault of her own and is entitled to redress according 62.1 (c).
Redress given as A10(a) average of race 1 and 2.
